Caesar had sailed from Brundisium with only 20,000 men (L.'s Rom. Hist, p. 380). Oving to tlie vigilance of the enemy the rest oi Caesar’s army was unable to foi· low him. His position was thus critical; cut off from the rest of bis army, and threatened by a force three times superior to his own. In his impatience he attempted to sail in a fisherman’s boat across the Adriatic to Brundisium, for his reinforcements, but the storm compelled him to turn back. In a short time the remainder of the army succeeded in crossing; at the battle of Pharsalus (in Thessaly), Pompey’s army was totally defeated (nc. 48). (L.'s Rom. Hist, p. 326 ff.)
